# Agent Tracing Rule

## Purpose

Track sub-agent orchestration with parent-child relationships and trace IDs.

## Activation

This rule is **always-on**. It activates automatically when an agent spawns a sub-agent.

## Behavior

### Sub-Agent Spawn

When a parent agent spawns a sub-agent, log in README format:

```
### [HH:MM:SS] AGENT:<parent>: Spawning sub-agent for <role>
> Trace ID: <unique-trace-id>
> Task: <task-description>
```

Example: `[AGENT:orchestrator] Spawning sub-agent for database-design`

### Sub-Agent Completion

When a sub-agent completes:

```
### [HH:MM:SS] AGENT:<sub-id>: Complete - <result-summary>
> Trace ID: <unique-trace-id>
> Duration: <time-elapsed>
```

Example: `[AGENT:sub-01] Complete - schema with 4 tables designed`

### Parent-Child Relationship

- Each sub-agent carries a `trace_id` linking it to its parent
- Sub-agents can spawn their own sub-agents (grandchildren)
- Trace IDs form a chain: `parent-id > child-id > grandchild-id`

## Trace ID Format

```
<timestamp>-<random>
Example: 20260319-103000-a7x9k
```

## Logging

All agent events are logged to `logs/workflow.md` with trace IDs for correlation.

## Example

```
[10:30:05] AGENT: Spawning sub-agent "database-designer"
> Parent: orchestrator
> Task: Design database schema for user domain
> Trace ID: 20260319-103005-m3n8p

[10:30:25] AGENT: Sub-agent "database-designer" completed
> Trace ID: 20260319-103005-m3n8p
> Duration: 20s
> Output: Schema with 3 tables designed
```
